name: Kepler-134
scenarioDescription:
The Kepler-134 Exoplanetary System

Kepler-134 is a star with 1.3339999999999999 times the mass of the Sun, and 1.18 times its radius. It is located 1102.57 light years away from the solar system.

Kepler-134 is known to have 2 exoplanets in orbit around it.

Kepler-134 b

Kepler-134 b was discovered by the Kepler observatory using the transit method. Its discovery was announced in 2014-03. Its semi-major axis is 0.06 astronomical units, as compared to Earth's which is 1 astronomical unit. It takes 5.32 Earth days to complete an orbit around its host star, Kepler-134.

The mass of Kepler-134 b is 5.05 times the mass of Earth. The radius of Kepler-134 b is 2 that of Earth. At 5.05 Earth masses, Kepler-134 b is a so called Super Earth. Super Earths could be terrestrial worlds like Earth, but they could also be ocean worlds or terrestrial worlds wrapped in a substantial atmosphere, in which case some refer to them as Mini Neptunes. No Super Earths are known to exist in our solar system, but if it exists, the so-called Planet Nine could very well be a super Earth, as it is hypothesized to have a mass between five and ten Earth masses.

Kepler-134 c

Kepler-134 c was discovered by the Kepler observatory using the transit method. Its discovery was announced in 2014-03. Its semi-major axis is 0.09 astronomical units, as compared to Earth's which is 1 astronomical unit. It takes 10.11 Earth days to complete an orbit around its host star, Kepler-134.

The mass of Kepler-134 c is 1.66 times the mass of Earth. The radius of Kepler-134 c is 1.26 that of Earth. At 1.66 Earth masses, Kepler-134 c is a so called Super Earth. Super Earths could be terrestrial worlds like Earth, but they could also be ocean worlds or terrestrial worlds wrapped in a substantial atmosphere, in which case some refer to them as Mini Neptunes. No Super Earths are known to exist in our solar system, but if it exists, the so-called Planet Nine could very well be a super Earth, as it is hypothesized to have a mass between five and ten Earth masses.
